Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Nigeria. The Nigerian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Entry and travel restrictions
Abuja and Lagos airports are closed to all international flights until 23 April. You should urgently contact your airline or tour operator if you are due to travel to or from Nigeria. Precautionary travel restrictions related to coronavirus have been extended to the United Kingdom and Enugu, Kano and Port Harcourt airports have closed to all international flights. For information on returning to the UK from Nigeria, see Return to the UK
Entry is restricted for travellers from the United Kingdom, Austria, China, Italy, Iran, South Korea, Spain, Japan, France, Germany, Norway, Netherlands, Sweden, Switzerland and the United States of America. All travellers returning from these countries prior to the restriction will be put into supervised self-isolation, monitored by Nigerian Centre for Disease Control and Port Health Services (NCDC). The Nigerian Government has also suspended the issuance of visa on arrival to travellers from these countries. Enugu, Kano and Port Harcourt airports are closed to all international flights.
The NCDC has implemented control measures at airports and an Emergency Operations Centre has been set up by NCDC. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
Local measures
From 20 March Lagos State announced that gatherings of 50 people or more have been banned. This includes bars, restaurants and weddings. While establishments will not be closed, there will be a Lagos State Police Taskforce checking venues that this is being complied with.
Further information
The NCDC have a 24 hour, toll free number for advice: (00234) (0) 800 970 000010. SMS: (00234) (0) 809 955 5577. Whatsapp: (00234) (0) 708 7110839. Mobile: (00234) (0) 703 670 8970 0010. The latest information can be found on their website.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
